1
00:00:57,724 --> 00:00:59,059
[indistinct chatter]

2
00:01:01,853 --> 00:01:03,897
[Aunt 1] Yeah, she'd like that, I'm sure.

3
00:01:03,981 --> 00:01:05,107
[Aunt 2] Can you imagine?

4
00:01:05,190 --> 00:01:07,192
[Aunt 1] [sighs] Such a good daughter!

5
00:01:07,484 --> 00:01:10,404
I mean, the poor thing's been taking care
of her for years.

6
00:01:10,904 --> 00:01:12,364
What she sacrificed.

7
00:01:12,698 --> 00:01:14,157
[screams]

8
00:01:14,241 --> 00:01:16,493
[Aunt 2]
At least now she will be free to go back.

9
00:01:19,746 --> 00:01:22,833
[Aunt 1] Can she ever really
perform again? It's been a decade.

10
00:01:22,916 --> 00:01:24,918
Well, what else is she gonna do?

11
00:01:25,002 --> 00:01:28,338
Uh, I don't know.
I don't think she even knows.

12
00:02:15,636 --> 00:02:16,678
[Charlotte] <i>Anton,</i>

13
00:02:17,012 --> 00:02:17,846
<i>Paloma,</i>

14
00:02:18,472 --> 00:02:19,973
<i>it's Charlotte Willmore.</i>

15
00:02:20,807 --> 00:02:21,725
[clears throat]

16
00:02:23,143 --> 00:02:23,977
<i>Anton,</i>

17
00:02:24,603 --> 00:02:25,479
<i>Paloma...</i>

18
00:02:27,814 --> 00:02:28,774
<i>Anton,</i>

19
00:02:28,857 --> 00:02:31,193
<i>Paloma, it's Charlotte Willmore.</i>

20
00:02:31,276 --> 00:02:33,487
<i>Yes, it's me. Hi.</i>

21
00:02:35,989 --> 00:02:37,074
[voicemail beeps]

22
00:02:37,574 --> 00:02:39,284
<i>Anton, Paloma. Hi.</i>

23
00:02:39,368 --> 00:02:41,787
<i>It's Charlotte Willmore.</i>

24
00:02:41,870 --> 00:02:44,206
<i>I don't know where you are in the world.</i>

25
00:02:44,289 --> 00:02:47,292
<i>Scouting young cellists</i>
<i>somewhere exotic, I'm sure.</i>

26
00:02:48,001 --> 00:02:53,048
<i>Anyway, um, I know it's been forever,</i>
<i>but my mother finally passed away</i>

27
00:02:53,131 --> 00:02:55,300
<i>and I'm not needed here anymore.</i>

28
00:02:55,384 --> 00:02:56,385
<i>So...</i>

29
00:02:56,468 --> 00:02:57,386
<i>if it's okay,</i>

30
00:02:57,469 --> 00:02:59,513
<i>I'd like to come and join you.</i>

31
00:03:40,762 --> 00:03:42,347
[music playing]

32
00:04:04,161 --> 00:04:05,162
[Anton] Charlotte.

33
00:04:28,602 --> 00:04:30,604
Paloma and I are so sorry
about your mother.

34
00:04:34,483 --> 00:04:37,360
[Anton] After a five-month search
over three continents,

35
00:04:37,444 --> 00:04:39,154
we are thrilled to bring our

36
00:04:39,237 --> 00:04:44,409
remarkable finalists together
in Shanghai for one last concert.

37
00:04:44,826 --> 00:04:46,995
The Bachoff Academy in Boston,

38
00:04:47,704 --> 00:04:50,707
founded by my grandfather Emil in 1927,

39
00:04:50,791 --> 00:04:53,668
is quite frankly the premiere 
private music facility

40
00:04:53,752 --> 00:04:56,046
for young cellists in the world.

41
00:04:56,129 --> 00:04:59,382
And each year, we teach hundreds
of day students in Massachusetts,

42
00:04:59,466 --> 00:05:02,677
but only a select handful
are given the opportunity

43
00:05:02,761 --> 00:05:06,264
privilege, really,
to reside and study at the Academy,

44
00:05:06,348 --> 00:05:09,434
which is why I'm so excited
that the winner tonight will receive

45
00:05:09,518 --> 00:05:12,729
a four-year live-in scholarship
to Bachoff.

46
00:05:12,813 --> 00:05:14,356
[audience applause]

47
00:05:18,193 --> 00:05:20,237
Now, the fact

48
00:05:20,320 --> 00:05:23,323
that my most prized protégé,

49
00:05:23,406 --> 00:05:27,327
Elizabeth Wells, one of the best
young cellists on the planet,

50
00:05:27,953 --> 00:05:30,872
will be judging tonight's final concert
is testament

51
00:05:31,289 --> 00:05:34,000
to just how talented
these three young ladies are.

52
00:05:35,669 --> 00:05:39,422
Listening to Lizzie play music so...
pure, so perfect

53
00:05:39,506 --> 00:05:42,634
is as close to God as you can get.

54
00:05:42,717 --> 00:05:45,136
Well, it's as close to God
as I want to get for the time being.

55
00:05:45,220 --> 00:05:46,972
-[audience laugh]
-[Anton] Uh...

56
00:05:47,055 --> 00:05:49,766
But Lizzie's not the only surprise we have
for you this evening.

57
00:05:49,850 --> 00:05:51,935
For four glorious years,

58
00:05:52,644 --> 00:05:55,480
I trained Charlotte Willmore at Bachoff.

59
00:05:55,856 --> 00:05:57,649
Charlotte was a rare and gifted talent

60
00:05:57,732 --> 00:06:02,153
poised for the type of greatness
achieved by very few,

61
00:06:02,237 --> 00:06:03,738
but then as all of you know,

62
00:06:04,197 --> 00:06:05,866
Charlotte's beloved mother, Ruth,

63
00:06:06,575 --> 00:06:07,492
got sick.

64
00:06:08,910 --> 00:06:13,373
Charlotte put her career on hold,
and went back home care for her mother.

65
00:06:13,957 --> 00:06:15,792
This is the heart of Charlotte.

66
00:06:25,677 --> 00:06:26,845
[machine whirs]

67
00:06:28,555 --> 00:06:32,309
I was thrilled that Charlotte reached out
to Paloma and myself,

68
00:06:32,934 --> 00:06:34,978
thrilled that after nearly a decade,

69
00:06:35,061 --> 00:06:36,271
she's back in our lives.

70
00:06:36,354 --> 00:06:39,649
Ladies and gentlemen,
our second judge for this evening,

71
00:06:39,733 --> 00:06:41,026
Charlotte Willmore.

72
00:06:51,036 --> 00:06:52,579
[boat horn blares]

73
00:06:55,749 --> 00:06:57,459
[Paloma]
It's baijiu. Chinese vodka.

74
00:06:57,542 --> 00:06:59,377
Two shots will have you
fluent in Mandarin.

75
00:06:59,461 --> 00:07:00,921
[laughs] Charlotte!

76
00:07:01,588 --> 00:07:02,964
Good, I was looking for you.

77
00:07:03,048 --> 00:07:05,884
You must remember these two
grueling taskmasters from the Academy?

78
00:07:05,967 --> 00:07:08,970
Oh, my goodness.
It's so wonderful to see you.

79
00:07:09,429 --> 00:07:10,597
Theis and Geoffrey.

80
00:07:10,680 --> 00:07:12,641
And after all these years! Mm.

81
00:07:13,516 --> 00:07:14,851
Charlotte, there you are!

82
00:07:16,102 --> 00:07:17,103
Would you excuse us?

83
00:07:17,854 --> 00:07:20,440
I want to introduce you,
before we have to go upstairs and start.

84
00:07:20,523 --> 00:07:22,192
She's so excited to meet you.

85
00:07:24,152 --> 00:07:27,280
And here she is, Charlotte, my star.

86
00:07:27,864 --> 00:07:29,240
-Elizabeth--
-Elizabeth Wells.

87
00:07:29,324 --> 00:07:30,450
Of course.

88
00:07:31,910 --> 00:07:33,203
Lizzie, please.

89
00:07:34,204 --> 00:07:35,163
Hey.

90
00:07:37,040 --> 00:07:40,210
Your music, Lizzie,
it's something more than beautiful.

91
00:07:42,337 --> 00:07:43,630
[Anton] I mean, I'm sorry.

92
00:07:43,713 --> 00:07:47,425
Am I the luckiest man in the world?
I don't even drink and I feel giddy drunk.

93
00:07:47,509 --> 00:07:50,011
My two most perfect students together.

94
00:07:50,887 --> 00:07:53,848
Oh, my goodness.
We gotta get this thing started.

95
00:07:54,432 --> 00:07:56,726
[sighs] I'm such a big fan.

96
00:07:57,394 --> 00:08:00,355
I know that sounds ridiculous,
but I've downloaded all of your music

97
00:08:00,438 --> 00:08:03,191
and that <i>New York Times</i> magazine profile
last month of you,

98
00:08:03,274 --> 00:08:05,944
those photos of you were amazing,
and the way--

99
00:08:06,486 --> 00:08:08,530
I was nine when I first saw you perform.

100
00:08:09,155 --> 00:08:11,825
You were 14 and everything I wanted to be.

101
00:08:12,283 --> 00:08:13,243
My idol.

102
00:08:13,785 --> 00:08:15,787
Please don`t be nervous
around me, Charlotte.

103
00:08:18,081 --> 00:08:19,916
I'm just so happy to finally meet you.

104
00:08:23,211 --> 00:08:24,212
[chuckles]

105
00:08:24,295 --> 00:08:25,672
[cello music plays]

106
00:08:51,197 --> 00:08:52,574
Wanna know a secret?

107
00:08:55,910 --> 00:08:57,662
The girl on the left is going to win.

108
00:08:57,746 --> 00:09:00,832
She's brilliant.
Leaves the other two in the dust.

109
00:09:03,835 --> 00:09:07,505
I agree, but that kind of takes
the drama out of it, doesn't it?

110
00:09:12,677 --> 00:09:13,887
You want drama?

111
00:09:16,848 --> 00:09:19,392
Watch that other girl's mother
in the blue dress.

112
00:09:22,645 --> 00:09:24,397
And the guy in the gray slacks.

113
00:09:25,190 --> 00:09:26,816
He's the father of the girl in the middle.

114
00:09:28,860 --> 00:09:30,695
There's something going on between them.

115
00:09:31,279 --> 00:09:32,864
They can't help themselves.

116
00:09:34,657 --> 00:09:37,285
[scoffs]
And right in front of their spouses.

117
00:09:38,244 --> 00:09:39,454
Just watch.

118
00:09:40,830 --> 00:09:42,957
I first noticed during semifinals.

119
00:09:44,375 --> 00:09:46,044
It's kind of hilarious.

120
00:09:48,129 --> 00:09:51,049
And... kind of hot.

121
00:09:54,052 --> 00:09:55,220
Just watch.

122
00:10:19,327 --> 00:10:20,370
Her hand...

123
00:10:42,058 --> 00:10:43,184
[sighs]

124
00:10:43,268 --> 00:10:45,520
I know I shouldn't spy, but...

125
00:10:47,605 --> 00:10:48,731
that...

126
00:10:51,067 --> 00:10:52,861
That gets me wet.

127
00:10:52,944 --> 00:10:53,987
[chuckles]

128
00:11:06,166 --> 00:11:08,835
[boat horn blares in distance]

129
00:11:29,189 --> 00:11:30,940
We've actually met once before.

130
00:11:32,692 --> 00:11:33,735
We have?

131
00:11:35,528 --> 00:11:38,281
It was the day you were leaving Bachoff.

132
00:11:39,699 --> 00:11:43,161
Your mom had just had her stroke,
and you had all your bags packed, and...

133
00:11:43,870 --> 00:11:49,167
I was just entering,
and I was nervous and excited, and...

134
00:11:50,168 --> 00:11:51,044
I saw you.

135
00:11:54,714 --> 00:11:55,757
My hero.

136
00:12:14,651 --> 00:12:15,652
[chuckles]

137
00:12:16,069 --> 00:12:17,570
That was a long time ago.

138
00:12:21,824 --> 00:12:23,243
Do you ever play anymore?

139
00:12:25,161 --> 00:12:27,580
It took me a while after I left Bachoff.

140
00:12:27,664 --> 00:12:29,916
Years to be honest, but now I...

141
00:12:30,458 --> 00:12:31,459
love it.

142
00:12:31,542 --> 00:12:33,670
-Because you're playing for yourself?
-Exactly.

143
00:12:33,753 --> 00:12:35,380
All that time with Anton,

144
00:12:36,631 --> 00:12:37,715
the practice,

145
00:12:38,424 --> 00:12:40,468
the performances,
the pressure to be perfect.

146
00:12:40,551 --> 00:12:42,095
-It was--
-I know.

147
00:12:42,845 --> 00:12:43,680
[chuckles]

148
00:12:45,974 --> 00:12:47,642
Do you ever think about leaving?

149
00:12:48,977 --> 00:12:50,061
Bachoff?

150
00:12:52,021 --> 00:12:54,399
It's my family. I can never.

151
00:12:55,942 --> 00:12:56,818
Never?

152
00:12:58,403 --> 00:12:59,570
No, never.

153
00:13:01,864 --> 00:13:04,450
And, anyway, the work.

154
00:13:05,159 --> 00:13:07,537
This special work.

155
00:13:08,746 --> 00:13:10,290
It's what's expected of us.

156
00:13:13,710 --> 00:13:15,044
I don't miss hearing that.

157
00:13:16,796 --> 00:13:20,341
Well, you'll be happy to know
I'm giving myself a little vacation.

158
00:13:20,425 --> 00:13:22,719
First one in forever. Starting tomorrow.

159
00:13:22,802 --> 00:13:24,053
-Amazing.
-I know.

160
00:13:24,512 --> 00:13:27,724
I know I can actually... sleep in.

161
00:13:27,807 --> 00:13:28,850
[both chuckle]

162
00:13:28,933 --> 00:13:32,687
Not dream about notes or scales,
rest my hands.

163
00:13:33,813 --> 00:13:35,106
Cause a little trouble.

164
00:13:35,898 --> 00:13:37,900
Have more than one drink in an evening.

165
00:13:38,693 --> 00:13:40,528
The baijiu is delicious.

166
00:13:41,529 --> 00:13:42,739
That is what I've heard.

167
00:13:43,948 --> 00:13:45,283
I better catch up.

168
00:13:55,251 --> 00:13:58,254
[both laugh]

169
00:13:58,338 --> 00:14:00,006
-[man grunts]
-[glass shatters]

170
00:14:04,052 --> 00:14:05,345
[speaking Mandarin]

171
00:14:07,430 --> 00:14:09,432
[grunting]

172
00:14:11,851 --> 00:14:13,519
Oh, Jesus!

173
00:14:13,603 --> 00:14:15,313
[speaking Mandarin]

174
00:14:23,488 --> 00:14:25,615
[man groans]

175
00:14:35,958 --> 00:14:37,960
[woman] Was it something he ate?

176
00:14:38,044 --> 00:14:40,129
I hope it isn't linked
to what's happening down south.

177
00:14:41,047 --> 00:14:42,507
What's happening down south?

178
00:14:45,301 --> 00:14:47,678
Some sort of hemorrhagic fever
near the Hunan border.

179
00:14:48,054 --> 00:14:50,181
Passed in the air.
Real contagion-like stuff.

180
00:14:54,519 --> 00:14:56,229
We were just scouting in Hunan.

181
00:14:56,312 --> 00:14:57,563
Oh, it can't be that.

182
00:14:57,647 --> 00:14:58,898
[scoffs] I sure hope not.

183
00:14:59,315 --> 00:15:02,068
You know how Anton likes to find his
protégés in remote places.

184
00:15:02,735 --> 00:15:05,613
-Hunan, Cambodia--
-Minnesota.

185
00:15:05,696 --> 00:15:06,781
Tampa.

186
00:15:07,949 --> 00:15:09,909
Will you go dancing with me later?

187
00:15:13,204 --> 00:15:14,163
Yes.

188
00:15:16,707 --> 00:15:17,750
Good.

189
00:15:17,834 --> 00:15:20,920
[Paloma] Lizzie, there you are.
Anton is asking for you.

190
00:15:21,629 --> 00:15:22,588
Come.

191
00:15:26,384 --> 00:15:27,844
[indistinct chatter]

192
00:15:30,555 --> 00:15:31,556
Elizabeth.

193
00:15:31,889 --> 00:15:34,142
Elizabeth. I was just telling
Geoffrey and Theis

194
00:15:34,225 --> 00:15:36,394
that I was hoping
that we could convince you to play

195
00:15:36,477 --> 00:15:39,480
one short piece, please.

196
00:15:40,398 --> 00:15:41,524
[exhales]

197
00:15:41,607 --> 00:15:45,194
Only if you can convince Charlotte
to play second cello with me.

198
00:15:46,154 --> 00:15:48,239
-My goodness. Yes, please.
-No.

199
00:15:48,322 --> 00:15:50,366
-No.
-No. no. no. We must.

200
00:15:50,450 --> 00:15:53,119
No. Lizzie, Lizzie. I couldn't.

201
00:15:53,202 --> 00:15:54,495
[Anton] Perfect. Please.

202
00:15:54,579 --> 00:15:56,372
Please! Yes, make it happen.

203
00:15:56,456 --> 00:15:58,583
-My goodness.
-Cello duet number three?

204
00:15:58,666 --> 00:15:59,876
[Anton] Oh, yes, perfect.

205
00:15:59,959 --> 00:16:02,336
-I know you still know it.
-[Theis] It's a dream come true.

206
00:16:02,420 --> 00:16:03,379
Lizzie...

207
00:16:04,380 --> 00:16:06,090
Lizzie, I'm an amateur now.

208
00:16:07,467 --> 00:16:10,094
You have been and always will be

209
00:16:10,178 --> 00:16:13,347
the person who makes 
my heart skip a beat when you play.

210
00:16:21,063 --> 00:16:23,274
Ladies and gentlemen.
Ladies and gentlemen.

211
00:16:23,941 --> 00:16:28,446
We are all about to witness
something extraordinary.

212
00:16:55,556 --> 00:16:57,099
[music plays]

213
00:19:12,693 --> 00:19:14,487
[moans]

214
00:19:15,738 --> 00:19:18,157
[moaning continues]

215
00:19:18,240 --> 00:19:19,617
[inaudible]

216
00:19:25,456 --> 00:19:26,499
[exhales]

217
00:19:38,594 --> 00:19:40,554
Have you ever been with a woman before?

218
00:19:42,306 --> 00:19:44,684
I've never been with anyone before.

219
00:19:47,269 --> 00:19:48,771
No one? Ever?

220
00:19:50,481 --> 00:19:52,900
My mom got sick, I went home.

221
00:19:53,901 --> 00:19:57,697
So, everything else just got put on hold.

222
00:20:01,033 --> 00:20:03,994
So, I'm your first.

223
00:20:04,078 --> 00:20:05,329
[chuckles]

224
00:20:05,830 --> 00:20:08,666
First and best.

225
00:20:08,749 --> 00:20:10,668
[laughs]

226
00:20:27,685 --> 00:20:29,478
I'm traveling out west tomorrow.

227
00:20:31,731 --> 00:20:32,815
Come with me.

228
00:20:34,066 --> 00:20:35,025
Really?

229
00:20:36,277 --> 00:20:37,236
Yeah.

230
00:20:38,279 --> 00:20:39,613
I'm doing it rough and tumble.

231
00:20:40,030 --> 00:20:42,158
Small buses, weird towns.

232
00:20:42,241 --> 00:20:44,827
As far away from first class as I can get.

233
00:20:45,786 --> 00:20:48,456
Unplugged from everything and everyone.

234
00:20:52,001 --> 00:20:53,627
I think we could have fun together.

235
00:20:54,962 --> 00:20:56,338
I think we could, too.

236
00:21:05,431 --> 00:21:07,767
I've never met anyone like you before.

237
00:21:10,853 --> 00:21:13,481
I mean, we're so different.

238
00:21:15,316 --> 00:21:16,400
And yet...

239
00:21:17,860 --> 00:21:19,737
we're more alike than it may seem.

240
00:21:26,869 --> 00:21:28,370
[inaudible]

241
00:21:34,585 --> 00:21:37,379
[pop music playing]

242
00:21:53,437 --> 00:21:54,522
[Charlotte] Good morning.

243
00:21:59,026 --> 00:22:01,278
[Lizzie] [groans] Good morning, you.

244
00:22:04,114 --> 00:22:05,032
[sighs]

245
00:22:05,115 --> 00:22:06,992
Are you as hungover as I am?

246
00:22:07,493 --> 00:22:08,786
Pretty much, yeah.

247
00:22:09,787 --> 00:22:12,540
I am out of practice
on the binge drinking.

248
00:22:13,582 --> 00:22:15,626
That Chinese vodka is brutal.

249
00:22:16,126 --> 00:22:17,211
Do you want some ibuprofen?

250
00:22:17,294 --> 00:22:19,296
Please. God, yes.

251
00:22:20,589 --> 00:22:22,049
[Lizzie]
My head is throbbing.

252
00:22:22,132 --> 00:22:23,717
I need like 50 of them.

253
00:22:28,597 --> 00:22:30,724
The pharmacy is open for business.

254
00:22:35,020 --> 00:22:36,689
What is that? Hair of the dog?

255
00:22:37,064 --> 00:22:38,399
It's the best cure.

256
00:22:39,358 --> 00:22:40,609
We're on vacation, right?

257
00:22:41,610 --> 00:22:43,404
[announcer speaking in Mandarin over PA]

258
00:22:51,120 --> 00:22:52,997
[Lizzie]
You really don't speak any Mandarin?

259
00:22:53,831 --> 00:22:55,457
Like, not even <i>ni hao?</i>

